ldnt have thought a good school would still be allowed to do this for that very reason. Wouldnt it be better to number children 1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2 etc. &#10;I would go to the head, I would complain to OFSTED and remove him from the school, I would probably put him into a special school, they will offer him the exact care he needs and he wont feel isolated. The teachers in a mainstream school probably havent experienced working with children who have a SEN, whereas teachers from a special school have specific training. If you do decide to keep him in this mainstream school, has he got an IEP? This is an individual education plan for a child with SEN which will have steps and goals to help your son achieve? If he hasnt I would report this to OFSTED too. Good luck with your decision x "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1093" language="en" documentId="4974" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Hayley L(82)" date="28-06-11 21:31" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/advice-support-40/special-needs-disabilities-support-502/598821-mainstream-special-needs-school-all.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4974" notes="" title="Mainstream or Special Needs School?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="456"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="457" end="1093"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>